Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/4%tsp}. When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{2} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}.

> TIP: Run the noodles under cold water to stop them sticking together.

While the noodles cook, halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips. Trim the @green beans{80%g} and cut into thirds. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the @British pork mince{240%g} and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once cooked, transfer the mince to a #bowl{}.

Pop the (now empty) frying pan back on medium-high heat. Add a drizzle of @?oil{drizzle} if needed. Once hot, add the green beans and pepper. Stir-fry until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes}. Turn the heat down to medium, then add the garlic and stir-fry for ~{30%seconds}. Add a splash of @water{} and immediately cover with a #lid{} or some #foil{}. Cook until the veg is tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add the cooked mince back into the frying pan along with the @black bean sauce{150%g} and @water for the sauce{2%tbsp}. Stir in the cooked noodles to coat them well, then reheat until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add a splash of water if needed. Remove from the heat.

Share the black bean noodles between your #bowls{}. Scatter over the spring onion to finish. Enjoy!